I think it's semantically wrong to mark the disconnection process as interrupted in case it was actually ended by a timeout. When the timeout expires, the thread will complete cleanly, there is no need for signaling.

Imagine you want to inspect the `screen`'s `disconnect` struct for debugging an abnormal closing of the app. Assume `SDL_EVENT_QUIT` never happens. When the timeout expires, the "scrcpy-dis" thread will push a `SC_EVENT_DISCONNECTED_TIMEOUT` event and terminate. Then this event triggers a call to `sc_disconnect_interrupt()`, which will mark `screen->disconnect.interrupted` as true even though the "scrcpy-dis" thread already terminated. From now on you could believe that this thread was interrupted in the middle of its `run()`, which is wrong, and you can't distinguish this case from an actual `SDL_EVENT_QUIT` anymore.

Of course you could also have a data race in the sense that both the timeout and the interruption would be triggered around the same time. In this case `screen->disconnect.interrupted` would be true even though the timeout already expired, but it wouldn't be semantically wrong since the user actually requested to quit. And if you really wanted to store the two states you could add `timed_out` in `struct sc_disconnect` alongside `interrupted`.

